## Delegation table — when to use which subagent

| Task shape | Use |
|---|---|
| Touches 3+ files, has trade-offs | Delegate to **planner** first, then **implementer** |
| Plan exists, just execute it | Delegate to **implementer** |
| Same error after 2 fix attempts | Delegate to **debugger** |
| Code is "done" — verify before merge | Delegate to **reviewer** |
| Single-file change, scope is obvious | Main agent does it directly — no delegation |

These match the subagents shipped in the Reliability Pack. If you have
not installed them, delete this section.

## Skills installed (and when they fire)

| Skill | Fires when the user says |
|---|---|
| code-review | "review", "look at", "audit", "check" + a diff or file |
| test-generation | "write tests", "add tests", "test this", "cover this" |
| refactor | "refactor", "clean up", "extract", "rename", "split", "DRY up" |
| doc-writing | "document", "write a README", "add docs", "docstring" |
| pr-description | "write a PR", "draft a PR description", "summarize the branch" |
| debug-loop-breaker | Same error after two fix attempts; "still broken", "didn't work" |

If the right skill doesn't fire, the activation hook
(`force-skill-eval.sh`) is either not installed or its path in
`settings.json` is wrong — see the Reliability Pack README.

## Conventions you must follow

- **Comments:** default to none. Only write a comment when the WHY is
  non-obvious. Never explain WHAT well-named code already shows.
- **Error handling:** validate at system boundaries (user input,
  external APIs). Trust internal code. No defensive checks for
  scenarios that can't happen.
- **Tests:** match the existing test framework. Never introduce a new
  one without explicit ask. Detect first (read `package.json`,
  `pyproject.toml`, etc.) — never guess.
- **Imports:** match existing project style (relative vs absolute,
  named vs default, alphabetical or not). Read a sibling file before
  writing.
- **Commits:** never amend pushed commits. Never `--no-verify`. Never
  `git push --force` to <main branch name>.
- **No new abstractions for hypothetical needs.** Three similar lines
  is fine. Build the abstraction the third time it's actually needed.

## What NOT to do without asking

- Add a new dependency. List the candidate, the size, and the alternative.
- Change `package.json` / `pyproject.toml` scripts.
- Rename or delete files outside the immediate scope of the task.
- Touch CI config (`.github/workflows/`, `vercel.json`, `vercel.ts`).
- Run `npm publish`, `pnpm publish`, or any deploy command.

